WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.800
 Hello, and welcome to our lecture on Kernigan and Ritchie Chapter 5, putting some context around it.

00:00:05.800 --> 00:00:10.380
 Chapter 5 is Functions and Program Structure.

00:00:10.380 --> 00:00:15.520
 So, the first thing I want to call your attention to is Section 5.1.

00:00:15.520 --> 00:00:23.760
 I actually think that Section 5.1 is the most poignant and beautiful section in the book.

00:00:23.760 --> 00:00:28.960
 Everything you've learned up till now, everything I've talked about, size of data, et cetera,

00:00:28.960 --> 00:00:34.740
 has led to the point where you can read 5.1 and understand every word of it.

00:00:34.740 --> 00:00:36.480
 You should enjoy reading it.

00:00:36.480 --> 00:00:42.040
 I think of it as like a love letter from the creators of C to future computer scientists.

00:00:42.040 --> 00:00:43.840
 So 5.1's important.

00:00:43.840 --> 00:00:46.520
 We'll talk a little bit about pointer arithmetic.

00:00:46.520 --> 00:00:53.720
 5.6, we'll look at sort of the duality between pointers and integers, then we'll hit call

00:00:53.720 --> 00:00:58.940
 by reference and call by value that are enabled in C by pointers, and then look at the big

00:00:58.940 --> 00:01:06.080
 as security hole that C has caused over the past 40 plus years, buffer overflow.

00:01:06.080 --> 00:01:12.400
 Now, the chapter gets a little dense in some of the sections, and so I'll just have you

00:01:12.400 --> 00:01:14.440
 skim some of those sections.

00:01:14.440 --> 00:01:20.880
 This is the essential example of pointers.

00:01:20.880 --> 00:01:23.520
 We have two variables, int, x, and y.

00:01:23.520 --> 00:01:27.640
 We have a variable px, which is of type pointer.

00:01:27.640 --> 00:01:29.140
 It points to an integer.

00:01:29.140 --> 00:01:30.520
 That's what int star means.

00:01:30.520 --> 00:01:38.560
 We store 42 in x, and we store the address of x into px using the ampersand operator,

00:01:38.560 --> 00:01:44.000
 and then we use the address of x, which is in px, and then we use a lookup operator or

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:49.560
 a dereference operator, star px, that says go to the memory location, point to 2 by px,

00:01:49.560 --> 00:01:52.360
 and load me an integer and put that into y.

00:01:52.360 --> 00:01:58.080
 And so we can see when we print out x is 42 and y is 42 and px is a long hexadecimal number

00:01:58.080 --> 00:02:04.660
 that is some memory location inside the actual computer, and so ampersand and asterisk and

00:02:04.660 --> 00:02:11.960
 int star, the star is a sort of a modifier for a type, are the important things.

00:02:11.960 --> 00:02:16.240
 One of the things that you've probably never seen in Python is the id function.

00:02:16.240 --> 00:02:22.200
 We've used functions like type and der, and there are ways for us to inquire about variables

00:02:22.200 --> 00:02:23.680
 and constants.

00:02:23.680 --> 00:02:27.420
 Id is a way to ask for the id of something.

00:02:27.420 --> 00:02:32.440
 Now in CPython, and just to be clear, there are multiple versions of Python.

00:02:32.440 --> 00:02:34.040
 CPython is the classic one.

00:02:34.040 --> 00:02:39.720
 It's the implementation of Python that happens to be written in C. There are other implementations

00:02:39.720 --> 00:02:42.640
 of Python.

00:02:42.640 --> 00:02:48.700
 And so what I'm telling you with this id function is something that will work for the moment

00:02:48.700 --> 00:02:51.720
 in CPython, but not necessarily every other one.

00:02:51.720 --> 00:02:56.280
 If you print it out and you say what is x and what is the id of x, it's kind of like

00:02:56.280 --> 00:02:57.820
 the address.

00:02:57.820 --> 00:03:03.400
 And if you look at the documentation, it says don't think this is the address, right?

00:03:03.400 --> 00:03:08.000
 It says the Python id function is not intended to be dereferenceable, meaning we're not supposed

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:10.660
 to look up memory from that.

00:03:10.660 --> 00:03:15.720
 The fact that it's based on the memory address is a CPython implementation detail that other

00:03:15.720 --> 00:03:18.680
 Python implementations do not follow.

00:03:18.680 --> 00:03:27.480
 Now if you download the source code, kr0501.py, I actually have a completely unauthorized

00:03:27.480 --> 00:03:31.440
 implementation of a lookup, a dereference.

00:03:31.440 --> 00:03:37.680
 And it has to know the type of the thing that it's dereferencing, y equals deref of px,

00:03:37.680 --> 00:03:42.360
 and it can then give me back that integer pointed to by the address.

00:03:42.360 --> 00:03:44.000
 But this is not guaranteed to work.

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:46.680
 It's not supposed to be how it works.

00:03:46.680 --> 00:03:53.360
 It just is, there is kind, things have addresses, and in CPython, at least for this particular

00:03:53.360 --> 00:03:58.560
 version of Python that I'm using, you can use them.

00:03:58.560 --> 00:04:01.720
 Pointers gives us the ability to do call by reference.

00:04:01.720 --> 00:04:07.280
 And so if you've done Python, you see that we had a slide in an early version of my Python

00:04:07.280 --> 00:04:13.160
 class that said sorry, Python doesn't do call by reference, it only does call by value.

00:04:13.160 --> 00:04:17.760
 And that means that within a function, you change the parameters and nothing happens.

00:04:17.760 --> 00:04:22.400
 But some languages do have call by reference, which means the parameters that come into

00:04:22.400 --> 00:04:28.360
 a function are somehow handles that allow us to actually change the values in the main

00:04:28.360 --> 00:04:31.280
 program or where we've been calling from.

00:04:31.280 --> 00:04:37.680
 So the language Pascal and C and C++, PHP and C# have this notion, a formal notion of

00:04:37.680 --> 00:04:38.960
 call by reference.

00:04:38.960 --> 00:04:44.280
 And languages that don't have it are like Python and Java and JavaScript.

00:04:44.280 --> 00:04:52.260
 Now there is a notion, the fact that I said this is for simple types like integers, objects

00:04:52.260 --> 00:04:56.040
 are passed in, but then if you call methods and objects, you can actually change the data

00:04:56.040 --> 00:04:57.680
 that the object has.

00:04:57.680 --> 00:05:01.320
 But it's not like you're changing the object, you're changing the object's data.

00:05:01.320 --> 00:05:03.080
 So let's take a look at a bit of code.

00:05:03.080 --> 00:05:06.040
 Now the first example is actually Pascal.

00:05:06.040 --> 00:05:12.200
 Now Pascal is a programming language that was written by Nicholas Wirth in Switzerland

00:05:12.200 --> 00:05:13.200
 in 1970.

00:05:13.200 --> 00:05:16.680
 And it had a call by reference.

00:05:16.680 --> 00:05:18.240
 And it had this notion of var.

00:05:18.240 --> 00:05:22.400
 And so you're creating a function named func, takes two parameters.

00:05:22.400 --> 00:05:27.240
 One is a call by value, which is a, and then the other one is call by reference, which

00:05:27.240 --> 00:05:28.240
 is b.

00:05:28.240 --> 00:05:31.280
 And we set a and b to two new numbers.

00:05:31.280 --> 00:05:35.320
 And then in the main program, we set x equals 42, y equals 43.

00:05:35.320 --> 00:05:40.360
 And then we call the function and you'll notice there's no extra syntax in the function.

00:05:40.360 --> 00:05:46.080
 And then we come back and you will see that the y variable is changed and the x variable

00:05:46.080 --> 00:05:47.080
 is not.

00:05:47.080 --> 00:05:52.400
 And then the c version of this, we have x equals 42, y equals 43.

00:05:52.400 --> 00:05:57.400
 And then when we call func, we say we're going to pass in x and then ampersand y, which is

00:05:57.400 --> 00:05:58.760
 the address of y.

00:05:58.760 --> 00:06:04.200
 And if you go back to the very first example in section 5.1, we're passing in a number,

00:06:04.200 --> 00:06:06.080
 which we're actually passing in by value.

00:06:06.080 --> 00:06:07.920
 But the value is the address.

00:06:07.920 --> 00:06:12.440
 And then inside the function, we take a and then a pointer to b, pb.

00:06:12.440 --> 00:06:17.360
 And we say that a is just an integer and pb is an address of an integer by adding the

00:06:17.360 --> 00:06:19.200
 little asterisk there.

00:06:19.200 --> 00:06:24.440
 So the address where it's at has been passed by value.

00:06:24.440 --> 00:06:28.360
 But using that value, we can dereference it and get to the thing.

00:06:28.360 --> 00:06:32.600
 So we say a equals 1 and then we say star pb equals 2.

00:06:32.600 --> 00:06:38.200
 That's a store 2 as an integer into the location pointed to by pb.

00:06:38.200 --> 00:06:42.000
 And then when you come back, the second parameter will have been changed, y will have been changed,

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:43.000
 and x will not be changed.

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:48.600
 And if we take a look at a few other languages, so here we have the c code again.

00:06:48.600 --> 00:06:53.920
 Python 1989 doesn't have the notion of pass by reference.

00:06:53.920 --> 00:07:01.400
 And so one of the things that I think is an excellent compromise that is the case in Python

00:07:01.400 --> 00:07:06.800
 is the notion of returning a tuple, not just a single value, but a tuple return.

00:07:06.800 --> 00:07:14.080
 And so that way we could, if we really wanted to get back a value, more than one value,

00:07:14.080 --> 00:07:19.160
 we could return a tuple and then in the main program, we assign the tuple.

00:07:19.160 --> 00:07:25.800
 So if we really wanted x and y to change from inside the function, we could do so by just

00:07:25.800 --> 00:07:30.200
 explicitly saying function is going to return two values and we're going to change them

00:07:30.200 --> 00:07:31.200
 both.

00:07:31.200 --> 00:07:38.080
 So if we look at php, which is 1994, we see a very elegant, I think, whenever you look

00:07:38.080 --> 00:07:41.040
 at php, you got to realize the dollar sign is just part of the variable name.

00:07:41.040 --> 00:07:44.400
 That's just the first character of all variables in php.

00:07:44.400 --> 00:07:49.580
 So what we do inside a function is we say ampersand dollar b, which is the second parameter

00:07:49.580 --> 00:07:53.220
 is b, dollar b, and we're expecting to change it.

00:07:53.220 --> 00:07:57.800
 And you'll note that we don't change the syntax inside the function, dollar b equals 2, dollar

00:07:57.800 --> 00:08:00.800
 a equals 1, the syntax doesn't change.

00:08:00.800 --> 00:08:05.560
 And when we make the call, func dollar x comma dollar y, we don't change that either, and

00:08:05.560 --> 00:08:07.200
 yet call by reference works.

00:08:07.200 --> 00:08:12.040
 So if you look at all these examples, other than the weird dollar sign convention, I would

00:08:12.040 --> 00:08:16.840
 say that the simplest and most elegant is probably the php implementation, right?

00:08:16.840 --> 00:08:21.440
 Because we don't have to do anything inside the function except I'm planning on changing

00:08:21.440 --> 00:08:22.440
 this.

00:08:22.440 --> 00:08:31.360
 Now, C#, which is much later, 2000, has this notion of ref, which is somewhat a throwback

00:08:31.360 --> 00:08:37.600
 to Pascal, but also it's the ampersand thing.

00:08:37.600 --> 00:08:44.020
 But the one thing I like about it is inside the call to func, you have to kind of agree

00:08:44.020 --> 00:08:51.000
 the calling code by saying ref x is in a sense agreeing that it is aware that x is likely

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:53.640
 to be changed by that function.

00:08:53.640 --> 00:08:55.440
 And so that's call by reference.

00:08:55.440 --> 00:09:00.760
 Now, we're in a C class, and so ampersand and asterisk are how we do it.

00:09:00.760 --> 00:09:07.240
 So again, it's really quite straightforward inside a C code, as long as you are very good

00:09:07.240 --> 00:09:11.040
 at understanding what the asterisk and ampersand do in C.

00:09:11.040 --> 00:09:16.460
 Another important thing that's easily understood with a very simple bit of code is pointer

00:09:16.460 --> 00:09:18.360
 arithmetic.

00:09:18.360 --> 00:09:23.120
 The key to pointer arithmetic is that a pointer to an integer is different than a pointer

00:09:23.120 --> 00:09:24.280
 to a character.

00:09:24.280 --> 00:09:28.600
 Now, both these pointers are the same size because they are an address, and addresses

00:09:28.600 --> 00:09:30.460
 are all the same size.

00:09:30.460 --> 00:09:35.320
 But if you add one to a character pointer, that actually adds one to the address.

00:09:35.320 --> 00:09:41.520
 And if you add one to an integer pointer, then it adds four, and that's because each

00:09:41.520 --> 00:09:44.600
 integer takes four characters.

00:09:44.600 --> 00:09:51.980
 And so when you're doing increments and subtracts, et cetera, when they're pointers, it increments

00:09:51.980 --> 00:09:54.160
 based on the type of the thing that's pointed to.

00:09:54.160 --> 00:09:58.240
 So a pointer is not just a pointer, it's a pointer to a thing with a type.

00:09:58.240 --> 00:10:02.920
 And when you're incrementing and decrementing, the type that's being pointed to is more important

00:10:02.920 --> 00:10:04.900
 than the fact that it's a pointer.

00:10:04.900 --> 00:10:09.260
 It goes up and goes down, but it doesn't always just go up and down by one.

00:10:09.260 --> 00:10:11.240
 Pointers are not integers.

00:10:11.240 --> 00:10:17.600
 So if you go back to chapter two, there was, from the book, a table of the sizes of things.

00:10:17.600 --> 00:10:23.520
 And so if you look in the PDP 11 integers, or 16 bits, in the Honeywell 6000, there are

00:10:23.520 --> 00:10:24.520
 36 bits.

00:10:24.520 --> 00:10:26.520
 In IBM 370, there are 32 bits.

00:10:26.520 --> 00:10:28.800
 In Interdata 832, there's 32 bits.

00:10:28.800 --> 00:10:34.320
 Now, I've added a line to this that tells the number of bits and addresses in these

00:10:34.320 --> 00:10:35.320
 systems.

00:10:35.320 --> 00:10:40.420
 And you can see, if you compare the int numbers to the address numbers, that in all the cases

00:10:40.420 --> 00:10:48.160
 except the PDP 11, the integer is larger than the address, which means that there is extra

00:10:48.160 --> 00:10:52.960
 space in the address, and we can almost treat addresses as unsigned integers.

00:10:52.960 --> 00:10:59.380
 Now, the PDP 11 is a little weird in that that 16 to 32 is a range of delivered computers

00:10:59.380 --> 00:11:06.580
 over the years, and not all computers had full memory, and not all applications used

00:11:06.580 --> 00:11:08.700
 the entire memory of the entire computer.

00:11:08.700 --> 00:11:15.660
 So most of the time, you can conveniently put an address into an integer, and then get

00:11:15.660 --> 00:11:21.000
 that address back out, and not have truncated that address or messed it up.

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:28.520
 So treating pointers as integers almost works, and the longer going history it was, the more

00:11:28.520 --> 00:11:30.660
 likely it did work.

00:11:30.660 --> 00:11:33.780
 Addresses are generally positive numbers that often start from zero.

00:11:33.780 --> 00:11:38.660
 Sometimes heap numbers come down, and sometimes stack numbers go up, or whatever.

00:11:38.660 --> 00:11:41.480
 But most computers did not come with a maximum memory installed.

00:11:41.480 --> 00:11:47.200
 And if you're a multi-user computer, you didn't give all the system's memory to every application,

00:11:47.200 --> 00:11:52.080
 and we tended to use very little memory in applications, we were very careful about it.

00:11:52.080 --> 00:11:57.840
 So we just never ran into the problem of our memory addresses not fitting into integers.

00:11:57.840 --> 00:12:03.080
 So in the early 70s, applications could get away with having a function that returned

00:12:03.080 --> 00:12:09.220
 an address, return it as an integer, and then copy it into a pointer without conversion.

00:12:09.220 --> 00:12:16.700
 And so, by like the early 80s, the notion of a void pointer gave us a way to have a

00:12:16.700 --> 00:12:21.420
 generic address, that is, a pointer to something we don't know what type it is.

00:12:21.420 --> 00:12:26.960
 Because all addresses are addresses, but what they point to is different.

00:12:26.960 --> 00:12:32.560
 And so, if you take a look at the alloc function, which we'll play a lot more in the next chapter,

00:12:32.560 --> 00:12:37.640
 the alloc says, oh, give me 42 bytes, and give it back to me as a pointer.

00:12:37.640 --> 00:12:41.420
 Give me a pointer to 42 new bytes that you just allocated.

00:12:41.420 --> 00:12:47.020
 So if you go in the early 70s, alloc returned an int, but then we would cast it to whatever

00:12:47.020 --> 00:12:48.060
 type we wanted.

00:12:48.060 --> 00:12:51.260
 So we would say alloc 42, it would give us an address, that'd be an integer, but then

00:12:51.260 --> 00:12:57.920
 we'd cast it to an integer star, which is a no-loss cast, and then we would store it.

00:12:57.920 --> 00:13:03.960
 By the time in the 1978 CNR book, we tended to call it a char star, because 42 is how

00:13:03.960 --> 00:13:06.100
 many characters we're gonna allocate.

00:13:06.100 --> 00:13:10.500
 And then you would take the pointer to a character and cast it to a pointer to an integer, and

00:13:10.500 --> 00:13:17.020
 so alloc of 42 would give us 14 integers, actually, I think if I got my multiplication

00:13:17.020 --> 00:13:18.200
 right.

00:13:18.200 --> 00:13:23.340
 But in modern C, we have this pointer, void pointer, which basically says, look, alloc

00:13:23.340 --> 00:13:28.200
 is gonna return an address, and you have to cast it to something.

00:13:28.200 --> 00:13:33.820
 So alloc 42 returns a void star, which is casted to an int star, which is a lossless

00:13:33.820 --> 00:13:38.220
 cast, and not something that's gonna confuse the compiler, and then we store it in our

00:13:38.220 --> 00:13:40.180
 int star variable.

00:13:40.180 --> 00:13:48.300
 And so void, everything you'll ever touch will be using void, but I just wanted to give

00:13:48.300 --> 00:13:53.500
 you a little bit of the history of it and why void's kind of not mentioned in this 1978

00:13:53.500 --> 00:13:54.500
 book.

00:13:54.500 --> 00:13:57.500
 Every time in class, I'm like, hey, it's time to learn about security, and everybody

00:13:57.500 --> 00:13:59.980
 kind of groans like, oh, no.

00:13:59.980 --> 00:14:04.520
 Back when I taught HTML injection and SQL injection and cross-site scripting in all my

00:14:04.520 --> 00:14:05.520
 previous classes.

00:14:05.520 --> 00:14:13.500
 And here's the classic XKCD, where the mom has named their child with a bit of SQL and

00:14:13.500 --> 00:14:18.040
 some single quotes and some comments, and that's all fun.

00:14:18.040 --> 00:14:24.500
 It's important that we as software developers are aware of how the things that we build

00:14:24.500 --> 00:14:31.200
 could be corrupted by those with evil intent, right?

00:14:31.200 --> 00:14:41.500
 So it has come time to talk about that for C. Probably the single worst security hole

00:14:41.500 --> 00:14:49.940
 in all of computing history, from 1950 to today, even before C was a thing, is what's

00:14:49.940 --> 00:14:52.300
 called buffer overflow.

00:14:52.300 --> 00:15:00.660
 And it has to do with the fact that there is no sense that a string of characters has

00:15:00.660 --> 00:15:02.500
 a length.

00:15:02.500 --> 00:15:06.540
 It has an allocated length, but it doesn't have a runtime length.

00:15:06.540 --> 00:15:12.580
 And so when we put more data into a string than can hold the string, it just keeps on

00:15:12.580 --> 00:15:14.420
 storing beyond the end of the string.

00:15:14.420 --> 00:15:17.960
 It doesn't like make a little more space.

00:15:17.960 --> 00:15:26.100
 And so this is from the Wikipedia page, where you have an eight-character string followed

00:15:26.100 --> 00:15:30.260
 by a two-character integer or something.

00:15:30.260 --> 00:15:35.560
 And we copy the string excessive, which is a nine-character, which includes nine characters

00:15:35.560 --> 00:15:38.500
 and the slash zero, the zero.

00:15:38.500 --> 00:15:44.340
 And that completely overwrites by just trying to write into the A string, it overwrites

00:15:44.340 --> 00:15:46.260
 the B variable as well.

00:15:46.260 --> 00:15:48.740
 And so that's buffer overflow.

00:15:48.740 --> 00:15:54.660
 It's sort of like somehow we're going to push too much into this variable so that it extends

00:15:54.660 --> 00:16:00.140
 where it's been allocated and that never is detected, and then it keeps going on.

00:16:00.140 --> 00:16:04.300
 And it means that you can do all kinds of things with buffer overflow.

00:16:04.300 --> 00:16:05.780
 You can change variables.

00:16:05.780 --> 00:16:08.540
 You can turn on super user permission.

00:16:08.540 --> 00:16:09.540
 Who knows?

00:16:09.540 --> 00:16:10.540
 You got to look at the source code.

00:16:10.540 --> 00:16:13.980
 You got to carefully construct a sort of nasty attack.

00:16:13.980 --> 00:16:21.540
 But the attack vector is the fact that string arrays bounds are not checked when we're copying

00:16:21.540 --> 00:16:22.540
 stuff in.

00:16:22.540 --> 00:16:26.600
 And if you write bad code or if the system writes bad code, it's just going to go wiping

00:16:26.600 --> 00:16:27.700
 out memory.

00:16:27.700 --> 00:16:34.380
 So it turns out that probably the worst offender of this is the get_s function.

00:16:34.380 --> 00:16:38.380
 And this was part of standard C for a long time.

00:16:38.380 --> 00:16:44.380
 And so here what I'm doing is I'm creating a 15-character string array, a character array,

00:16:44.380 --> 00:16:47.900
 which is 15 elements, and I'm calling get_s.

00:16:47.900 --> 00:16:53.060
 And the problem with get_s is like somebody's going to give us that data and it's not us.

00:16:53.060 --> 00:16:54.820
 And then I print it out.

00:16:54.820 --> 00:17:03.080
 So the first thing you see is when I compile a bit of code that has get_s, the compiler

00:17:03.080 --> 00:17:04.180
 is upset.

00:17:04.180 --> 00:17:10.260
 I have greatly simplified the errors.

00:17:10.260 --> 00:17:13.960
 It comes up with three errors and this is a subset of one of the errors.

00:17:13.960 --> 00:17:17.420
 The compiler is telling you don't use get_s.

00:17:17.420 --> 00:17:21.060
 If you didn't hear what I said the first time, don't use get_s.

00:17:21.060 --> 00:17:23.540
 And so the compiler is not happy.

00:17:23.540 --> 00:17:27.980
 But it's like, you know, people write that so we're going to run it, okay?

00:17:27.980 --> 00:17:37.700
 A.out, which starts the code, as soon as that line get_s runs, the runtime of the C standard

00:17:37.700 --> 00:17:43.740
 sdio.h says before it prompts us for the data, it actually adds a print statement.

00:17:43.740 --> 00:17:45.020
 It's not our print statement.

00:17:45.020 --> 00:17:50.100
 It's the library saying you really, really should not be using get_s.

00:17:50.100 --> 00:17:54.540
 And if you think this program is trustworthy, you're probably wrong.

00:17:54.540 --> 00:18:00.740
 So I type hello world, which is 11 characters, hello space world.

00:18:00.740 --> 00:18:02.260
 Yeah, it's 11 characters.

00:18:02.260 --> 00:18:03.260
 Hello world's 11 characters.

00:18:03.260 --> 00:18:05.340
 I type 11 characters in.

00:18:05.340 --> 00:18:08.860
 That includes the 12th character, which is the backslash zero.

00:18:08.860 --> 00:18:16.420
 And that fits into s15, a 15 element character array in the variable s.

00:18:16.420 --> 00:18:17.820
 So the program works just fine.

00:18:17.820 --> 00:18:21.940
 Then I type a.out again, and it once again tells me, please don't use get_s.

00:18:21.940 --> 00:18:24.180
 You're going to be in so much trouble.

00:18:24.180 --> 00:18:30.060
 And now I type instead a bunch of, a hello and a bunch of spaces in then world.

00:18:30.060 --> 00:18:34.780
 And it prints out hello bunch of spaces in world, but has overwritten all kinds of unknown

00:18:34.780 --> 00:18:38.840
 data after the s15.

00:18:38.840 --> 00:18:43.020
 So that's, you know, that's like 30 or 25 or 30 characters.

00:18:43.020 --> 00:18:48.140
 Then the first 15 are in s, but then the next 15 are somewhere else.

00:18:48.140 --> 00:18:53.780
 And s is on the stack because it's an automatic variable in main, and it goes wiping out the

00:18:53.780 --> 00:18:54.780
 rest of the stack.

00:18:54.780 --> 00:19:00.980
 Now it turns out that the C runtime puts things on the stack to kind of mark or to catch this

00:19:00.980 --> 00:19:01.980
 overflow.

00:19:01.980 --> 00:19:06.140
 And so what happens is as soon as that code finishes, it says abort trap six, which is

00:19:06.140 --> 00:19:11.580
 basically the C runtime saying, you know what, I'm not going to let this program proceed

00:19:11.580 --> 00:19:15.540
 any further because there has been an array that got messed up.

00:19:15.540 --> 00:19:21.460
 And it's not that it caught, it's not that it caught the array messing up.

00:19:21.460 --> 00:19:23.100
 It didn't know how long it was.

00:19:23.100 --> 00:19:24.500
 It just put characters in.

00:19:24.500 --> 00:19:28.620
 But what it did is I put something after the array and then it checked for it later.

00:19:28.620 --> 00:19:29.620
 And that got wiped out.

00:19:29.620 --> 00:19:33.660
 And it's like, okay, you wiped out my magic little secret.

00:19:33.660 --> 00:19:36.760
 And so I'm going to not let you continue.

00:19:36.760 --> 00:19:40.780
 And so we don't want you to use get_s.

00:19:40.780 --> 00:19:41.980
 And this is a buffer overflow.

00:19:41.980 --> 00:19:46.500
 And I can give you, eventually maybe we will look at some much more complex examples of

00:19:46.500 --> 00:19:51.540
 this where we try to like use something like get_s to manipulate what the program does

00:19:51.540 --> 00:19:53.700
 rather than just blow the program up.

00:19:53.700 --> 00:19:57.820
 But this is a very simple example of buffer overflow.

00:19:57.820 --> 00:20:06.980
 So in summary, pointers are the beautiful, most beautiful part of C. They're complex,

00:20:06.980 --> 00:20:11.860
 but basically pointers make it so that a high level language can function like a low level

00:20:11.860 --> 00:20:12.860
 language.

00:20:12.860 --> 00:20:17.420
 If we don't have pointers, and I mean not even kind of crappy Python ones, I mean pointers

00:20:17.420 --> 00:20:23.060
 that we can look up and then dereference officially and formally and not have it be a sneaky way

00:20:23.060 --> 00:20:24.660
 that we're doing it.

00:20:24.660 --> 00:20:28.340
 That means that you can do the things that operating systems need to do, the kinds of

00:20:28.340 --> 00:20:32.460
 things that we used to write assembly language for, meaning we're going to, here's a buffer

00:20:32.460 --> 00:20:33.460
 of memory.

00:20:33.460 --> 00:20:34.460
 We're going to copy this buffer.

00:20:34.460 --> 00:20:35.460
 We're going to do another thing.

00:20:35.460 --> 00:20:41.580
 There's another buffer and there's a linked list of all the different buffers.

00:20:41.580 --> 00:20:45.500
 So understanding pointers leads you to the path of assembly language, machine language,

00:20:45.500 --> 00:20:47.780
 and then ultimately hardware.

00:20:47.780 --> 00:20:51.660
 So you should not rush through this material.

00:20:51.660 --> 00:20:55.380
 Pointers are really, really important.

00:20:55.380 --> 00:20:59.580
 Everything we're going to do from now on, pointer is just, I'm just going to say pointer,

00:20:59.580 --> 00:21:03.340
 pointer, pointer, just like I say object-oriented all the time, I'm going to say pointer all

00:21:03.340 --> 00:21:04.860
 the time.

00:21:04.860 --> 00:21:10.940
 Pointers 5.7 and 5.10 through 5.12 are a little dense, so what I really want you to do is

00:21:10.940 --> 00:21:15.740
 understand the stuff I just talked about and the corresponding sections.

00:21:15.740 --> 00:21:21.140
 And chapter six will be more fun because we'll be doing much more with the pointers rather

00:21:21.140 --> 00:21:22.300
 than just what is a pointer.

